##How did the World Health Organization's "whistle-blowing" timeline -- a window of opportunity -- get lost?

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

"The countries concerned should grasp the 'window' for Disease Prevention and control, " said World Health Organization director-general Tan Desai many times, the first warning came in early February, when the new pneumonia epidemic in China was still very serious. His warning, however, does not appear to have prompted more countries to take the necessary action.
"Right now, about 99 percent of the cases are in China, " Tan said in Geneva on Feb. 4. "The number of cases in other countries is limited, but that doesn't mean the situation won't change. ". At the time, many Western countries really thought they could shut out the new pneumonia or that it would not cause a pandemic even if it entered the country.
China has paid a huge price in the past two months in exchange for a "window period" for the world to control the epidemic, but World Health Organization's repeated whistle-blowing has not been taken seriously by some countries, and even some Western politicians have launched smear attacks against China and even the WHO, now the epidemic has spread around the world, the world is under tremendous pressure.
Let's go back to World Health Organization's whistle blowing timeline of the past two months and see how the window of opportunity is being missed around the world, especially in the West.
